Playing a Sorcerer is not for the weak-hearted, the anxious, or the person who wants to do a lot of mob damage.  Sorcerer is purely crowd control.  The Sorcerer can be played aggressively through offense, but serves more purpose through wise defense and supportive offense.<P>Specs<P>Mind is the bread and butter of sorcerer.  Its our lifeline.  It gives you the uncanny ability of mezzing numerous mobs, charming humanoids up to your level, debuffing (constitution and strength) of all enemies, and can change a bad situation into a favorable one.<P>IMO, Body or Matter should be chosen and not both.  I'm currently Mind/Body, but after a few talks with other notable Sorcerer's I've found that Mind/Matter could have been a viable option these days, whereas it wasn't in the past(dmg cap on mind nuke).  <P>If you go Mind/Matter, the spec dots will cost you roughly the same amount as the bodyspec's nuke, but you now have AoE over direct damage.  This is perfect for RvR(more targets damaged=more rps), but limits the amount of casting you could do during PvE since most higher level mobs are Bring-A-Friend(AoE will break mez or piss of the mob making it unmezzable), limiting you to lifetap as your main nuke.<P>If you follow the path I took in Mind/Body, you would want to get your mind up to 34(last AoE mezz) and then put the rest in body.  Mind/Body will give you a AoE Dex/Quickness debuff, mind nuke, and a 2 second snare. You can then collect as many matter items that you can find, so you can cut the cost of dots down in RvR.  You will also want to put more into mind near the beginning and slowly catch up with body(3 mind to 1 body) in the beginning since we have the uncanny ability to mez higher level mobs just as well as any other con if you have good mind specced.<P>Tactics<P>Sorcerer has to be aware of all things and should probably set ground rules on mob encounters as he/she enters a group.  Its well known that Sorcerers should be put on protect since they take more aggro than clerics if they are doing their job right. Tell the group to let you AoE mez and they fight whatever resists or the closest mob.<P>If mez resists the first time, quickcast it again.  80% of the time you will get it on the second try.  This means that the group has to have a little more faith in you before engaging extra mobs that make it to the group.  If you fail the second time, just /y and the group will know that you have failed mez.  <P>You should stand beside your tanks when pulls come so you have time to get off the 4-second aoe mez.  Then you should back up behind the tanks, giving you view over the entire battle.<P>Confusion<P>In your earlier levels(pre-20), the confuse line spells you receive are excellent for spreading the wealth of dmg taken.  If your group seems like its in trouble and the main tank will probably fall, cast confuse and the mob will switch between most of your party allowing the healer time to help the tank.  IMO, the higher level confuse spell shouldn't be used unless you are running away from mobs.  I have my confuse on a hotbar with macroed /face.  Run away, zoom out, target mob, /face, cast, run away.<P>Theurg and Sorc: Masters of Crowd control<P>If you have a theurg in your party, both of you target the incoming mobs and have your theurg cast AoE root at the same time you cast AoE mez.  The root is slightly faster, so your mez will land right after the root, which means that the mobs would have to resist both root and mez in order to get to the group(damn near impossible if timed properly). Beware that if the root lands after mez, it will overwrite your mez and breaks a lot faster than mez(you can remez the mobs).  You can tell which mob is rooted because their feet will still move, whereas a mezzed mob's feet will not.<P>Clerics and Sorc:  Mez vs Insta-mez<P>Unfortunately, cleric's pbae mez overwrites a sorcerer's mez, but not vice-versa.  This means that if you are a little late getting mez to work and your cleric uses insta-mez, you have to watch over the cleric for 10 seconds until it breaks.  I usually wait 7 seconds and cast aoe mez so that it lands shortly after the cleric's insta mez breaks.<P>I won't delve into soloability because I don't solo much.  In fact, the better you get at crowd control, the more groups you will get and most likely more tells you will get to join groups.<P><BR>Jamal The Sorcerer<BR>Lancelot Server
</FONT>
