<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Good information Jamal, though I would throw out a counter point to a couple of yours under Tactics.<P>I find that standing as far away from your tanks as possible is an easier way to keep your group trained while your mezzing, on an average pull of 2-3 monsters, at least one if not both of the extras will go right for you(yes at the sorc, not the other 6 people in the group standing at various points closer to you /boggle) which allows you a clear and easy path to target, as well as spacing them away so that if for whatever reason you do get resisted, it makes it easy for the tanks who are peeling in your group to get the correct one and go back to fighting. It also works fabulously with a paladin, as most times all of the adds will be going straight for the paladin, and if you are resisted, you'll have enough time for another cast before anyone has to start panicking. <P>As far as using AoE mez,, this is all a matter of specialization, I sacrificed mindto get the level 28 body nuke as soon as possible, and made more than do with the single target mez, it just requires a lot more patience and training of your group. Even hunting pygmies i usually wound up using the single target, and probably still will even after i finally get the 34 aoe mez next level. Of course it's all a matter of preference, and i wouldn't argue for one or the other, but for someone who is still using the level 24 aoe mez at 42, the single target does have its merits if you can handle it.(Also great for making the smite clerics jealous if you don't allow a whole mob of things to get inside their mez range =).<P>Shalandra Ilveyorn<BR>Enigmatic of 42 seasons on Percival<BR>Proud Member of The Dawn's Chosen
